text:
6:45 "What is the lore of Kirby?" Oh boy, do you have the time? Because Kirby lore is unironically some of the deepest and darkest that exists in any Nintendo property.
Highlights include the Mirror World from an old GBA game being relevant to a certain villain's backstory, ancient wish-granting supercomputers that travel the cosmos, the remains of Earth existing in the form of Shiver Star in Kirby 64, four star warriors sealing away a great evil that happens to share lots of traits with Kirby and may be some primordial form of Dark Matter, a recurring evil entity in the series, a certain butterfly appearing in almost every Kirby game opening cutscene (including this one), and some ancient precursor species who can use technology to create portals through space (which may be relevant later in this game).
This game put lore in the figure descriptions, but if you ever play one of the older games (I'm not sure about before, but definitely the mainline games from Super Star Ultra to Star Allies), pause during boss fights. Every major boss has flavor text on the pause screen, and endgame/postgame boss flavor text is almost always lore relevant.
author: @JohnDoe-yp3zv

text:
Kirby is a young star warrior who had the weight of the world thrusted upon his shoulders. He was called upon by the stars to save Popstar from a dark and all-encompassing threat, but arrived a bit too early...early enough to prove his mettle against a the leader of the Meta Knights and to rescue Dream Lands food supply (and stars) from the clutches of it's greedy king (and future rival in gluttony). 

He will later go on to fight against nightmares, anti-creation, a dark swordsman from the mirror world, two cunning wizards, a queen bee, a gang of necro-space pirates, a gang of airship pirates, a corporate tyrant, two warriors sealed away for their immense power, two wishing stars, a group of cultists and a his polar opposite.
